title: Fitness Test: FTP and Threshold HR
description:
This fitness test helps you to set your power or heart rate thresholds for Training Peaks.

Warm Up:
12 mins in Z2,
5 x (15 secs in Z4 + 45 secs easy in Z2).

Main Set:
20 mins maximal steady state time trial. Go as hard as you can sustain for 20-minutes.

Warm Down:
5 mins in Z2.

NOTES:
1/ Alternatively, if you have a bike training device with its own "FTP" test protocol, you could use that instead.

2/ If using a smart trainer (for example a Wahoo Kickr), DO NOT use ERG mode for this test.
https://myprocoach-help.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/360022308391-Erg-Mode-On-or-Off-

TIP: Have a fan and/or air conditioning, so that heat stress is not a limiting factor for this test.
coachComments:
FUNCTIONAL THRESHOLD POWER (FTP)
Take your average power for the 20-minute test and multiply it by 95% for your FTP.

THRESHOLD HEART RATE (THR)
Take your average HR for the 20-minute test and reduce by 6 beats, this is your bike THR.

ENTER THRESHOLDS AND ZONES
Check this article and short video to enter your thresholds and training zones into your TrainingPeaks settings:
https://bit.ly/EnterBikeZones

RATE OF PERCEIVED EXERTION (RPE)
To ride to feel (RPE), complete the test and note the distance. Use this to track progress in future tests.

Click this link for more details of this fitness test:
https://myprocoach-help.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/360001077251-Bike-Field-Test-FTP-Threshold-HR

title: Aerobic Endurance Run
description: A steady run, mainly in Z1-Z2. You should be able to chat at this intensity. This is your long run for the week and it will progress in duration. They will gradually build your endurance.
coachComments:
Phil's Training Tip:

Your pace on these runs will depend on several factors, such as the terrain, elevation and conditions. Try not to get too worried about sticking to a set pace. Heart Rate or Rate of Perceived Exertion can work well instead, helping you to listen to your body.

title: Fitness Test: Threshold Pace and HR
description:
This fitness test helps you to set your pace and heart rate thresholds and training zones for TrainingPeaks.

Warm Up:
5 mins in Z2 (easy/steady),
4 x (30 secs accelerating from Z2 to Z4 + 30 secs recoveries in Z1).

Main Set:
Run for 30 mins at the fastest pace you can maintain for the duration. Record your average pace and ideally average heart rate too.

Warm Down:
5 mins in Z1 to Z2 (easy).
coachComments:
THRESHOLD RUN PACE
Complete the test and note your threshold pace (average pace for the 30-minute interval)

THRESHOLD HEART RATE (THR)
Take your average HR for the 30-minute test, this is your Run THR.

Check this article and short video to enter your thresholds and training zones into your TrainingPeaks settings:
https://bit.ly/EnterRunZones

title: OPTIONAL Aerobic Endurance Ride
description:
This workout works well on an indoor bike trainer; you can also do it outside. It's not supposed to be high intensity, so keep a lid on this one. You will improve your fat-burning and efficiency.

Warm Up:
10 mins in Z2.

Main Set:
5 x (5 mins in upper Z2 + 60 sec recoveries in low Z2),
5 x (3 mins in upper Z2 + 30 sec recoveries in low Z2).

Warm Down:
5 mins in low Z2.
coachComments:
Phil's Training Tip:

Optional workouts will benefit your training but only if they are optimal to your schedule and fitness. If you can easily fit the workout into your diary without causing stress and/or fatigue then you will gain fitness.

Don't be tempted to squeeze optional workouts into a busy schedule. Save your physical and psychological energy for the next session and future training.

title: Aerobic Endurance Ride
description: Ride at an easy/steady intensity, mainly in Z2 today. You should be able to chat at this intensity. This ride will improve your efficiency for using fat for fuel and increase your ability to transport oxygen to your working muscles.
coachComments:
Phil’s Training Tip:

When you're exercising for longer than about 1 hour 20 you need to consume carbohydrate during your workouts to stop your energy levels from dropping too much. Aim for the equivalent of an energy gel every 30 minutes for training. It doesn't even have to be an "energy" product. You could have a cereal bar, a banana, a sugary drink or whatever you like. It just needs to consist mainly of carbohydrate. And water is fine for hydration.

title: Easy Run Off The Bike
description: Get off your bike and settle into a nice steady run in Z2. Don't over stride.
coachComments: Running straight off the bike is a time-efficient way to get your sessions done. It also prepares your body for the specific race-day requirements of triathlon.

title: Aerobic Endurance Ride
description: Nice and easy ride today, enjoy and stop for a coffee if you like!
coachComments:
Phil’s Training Tip:
Your "cadence" is the count of how many pedal revolutions you do per minute. Whereas, "power output" is a combination of your cadence AND how hard you pedal. Therefore, to increase your power output you would need to pedal faster in the same gear. Or pedal at the same cadence, but in a bigger gear.

What's the Best Cadence?
Research is unclear on the single "best cadence" to ride at. One study suggests that athletes subconsciously self-select the cadence that's most efficient at a given time. The best cadence for your needs can also depend on the type of cyclist you are, your aerobic fitness, physique, leg strength and exercise intensity. For example, your cadence might naturally be higher in a race, and lower during an easy training ride.

What Cadence to Target?
85-90 rpm is ideal for many riders, but don't force yourself to ride at that cadence if it doesn't feel right. Try not to get too worried about your cadence - it may naturally change over time anyway. You're better off focusing on increasing your power output and reducing your aerodynamic drag.

title: Fitness Test: FTP and Threshold HR
description:
This fitness test helps you to set your power or heart rate thresholds for Training Peaks.

Warm Up:
12 mins in Z2,
5 x (15 secs in Z4 + 45 secs easy in Z2).

Main Set:
20 mins maximal steady state time trial. Go as hard as you can sustain for 20-minutes.

Warm Down:
5 mins in Z2.

NOTES:
1/ Alternatively, if you have a bike training device with its own "FTP" test protocol, you could use that instead.

2/ If using a smart trainer (for example a Wahoo Kickr), DO NOT use ERG mode for this test.
https://myprocoach-help.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/360022308391-Erg-Mode-On-or-Off-

TIP: Have a fan and/or air conditioning, so that heat stress is not a limiting factor for this test.
coachComments:
FUNCTIONAL THRESHOLD POWER (FTP)
Take your average power for the 20-minute test and multiply it by 95% for your FTP.

THRESHOLD HEART RATE (THR)
Take your average HR for the 20-minute test and reduce by 6 beats, this is your bike THR.

coachComments:
Today's Technique Focus:
Driving the Thigh.

Concentrate on driving the thigh of your swing leg forward a little more forcefully than you normally do. The more forceful forward/upward movement of this leg will create a counterbalancing downward/backward action in your opposite leg as it comes into contact with the ground. (Think of the way your free arm moves in opposition to your throwing arm when you throw a ball hard.)
Feel free to concentrate on driving only one thigh throughout a workout or, if you can manage it, to concentrate on driving both thighs. (The average stride rate being in excess of 150 per minute, it can be difficult to focus your attention properly on both legs when using this proprioceptive cue). This cue will help you refine the coordinated timing of movements between your two legs and enhance your stride stiffness.
